      {
        "type": "email",
        "html": "<p>Hello {first_name, \"there\"},</p><p>I've been heads down for the last few days, working on the piece I really wanted to write about TikTok, and I finally got it finished and published this morning. Even if you're not really interested in the platform, please do give it a read. It's just as much about how we should handle publishing on social platforms as it is about the specific problems that TikTok itself creates.</p><p>Now that's done, it's back to normal service this week — and hopefully finishing that series on community I started last week. But first, let's talk TikTok, the BBC and China…</p>"
      },
      {
        "children": [
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "TikTok is becoming a social strategy headache",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          }
        ],
        "direction": "ltr",
        "format": "",
        "indent": 0,
        "type": "heading",
        "tag": "h2",
        "version": 1
      },
      {
        "children": [
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "I have nearly two decades of history advocating for news organisations taking advantage of publishing on social platforms under my belt. Sure, I had and have misgivings about Facebook, but the general thrust of my work has always been that we need to be where the people are, and figure out what to do with the relationships we build there.",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          }
        ],
        "direction": "ltr",
        "format": "",
        "indent": 0,
        "type": "paragraph",
        "version": 1
      },
      {
        "children": [
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "So, it’s really strange to find myself now cautioning about investing too much time and effort on TikTok because its future outside China is looking distinctly rocky right now. I’ve spent a lot of time thinking about this over the last couple of months, and here’s how I recommend ",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          },
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 2,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "you",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          },
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": " think about the situation:",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          }
        ],
        "direction": "ltr",
        "format": "",
        "indent": 0,
        "type": "paragraph",
        "version": 1
      },
      {
        "type": "bookmark",
        "version": "1.0",
        "url": "__GHOST_URL__/2023/03/tiktok-should-news-organisations-be-on-the-platform-now/",
        "metadata": {
          "url": "__GHOST_URL__/2023/03/tiktok-should-news-organisations-be-on-the-platform-now/",
          "title": "TikTok: should news organisations be on the platform now?",
          "description": "TikTok is beloved of Gen Z — but a lot less popular amongst Western governments. With a US ban looming, here’s how to rethink your strategy.",
          "author": "Adam Tinworth",
          "publisher": "One Man & His Blog",
          "thumbnail": "__GHOST_URL__/content/images/2023/03/tiktok-gen-z-china.png",
          "icon": "__GHOST_URL__/content/images/size/w256h256/2021/05/COV-1638-3865.png"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalrule"
      },
      {
        "children": [
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "We’re nowhere near peak subscriptions yet",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          }
        ],
        "direction": "ltr",
        "format": "",
        "indent": 0,
        "type": "heading",
        "tag": "h2",
        "version": 1
      },
      {
        "children": [
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "I do wonder about the journalism business’s obsession with “peak”. We keep talking about “peak podcasts” or “peak newsletters”, but did we ever talk about “peak magazines”?",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          }
        ],
        "direction": "ltr",
        "format": "",
        "indent": 0,
        "type": "paragraph",
        "version": 1
      },
      {
        "children": [
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "Anyway, friend of the blog, the ever-insightful Greg Piechota, researcher-in-residence at INMA, has been looking at subscription levels in news, and his thesis is that we’re a long way off “peak subscription” yet. Sure, this will be a challenging few years for subs businesses, but there’s still plenty of headroom for growth.",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          }
        ],
        "direction": "ltr",
        "format": "",
        "indent": 0,
        "type": "paragraph",
        "version": 1
      },
      {
        "type": "bookmark",
        "version": "1.0",
        "url": "https://www.inma.org/blogs/conference/post.cfm/media-companies-have-not-reached-their-subscriptions-peak",
        "metadata": {
          "url": "https://www.inma.org/blogs/conference/post.cfm/media-companies-have-not-reached-their-subscriptions-peak",
          "title": "Media companies have not reached their subscriptions peak",
          "description": "Greg Piechota, researcher-in-residence at INMA and lead of the INMA Readers First Initiative, shared his original research during the INMA Media Subscriptions Summit in Stockholm last week, updating attendees on the state of subscriptions since the pandemic.",
          "author": "Josefin Olevik",
          "publisher": "INMA",
          "thumbnail": "https://www.inma.org/files/images/blogs/feature_photos/Conference_SubSummit-MAR23-Greg-Piechota-1800.jpg",
          "icon": "https://www.inma.org/favicon.ico"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalrule"
      },
      {
        "children": [
